    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>MORE BRAZILIANS BORROWING</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Jennifer L. Rich</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Rich, Jennifer L</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Brazilian bank borrowing rose in April for 10th consecutive month as economic recovery increased consumers' appetite for credit; banks lent $33 billion in April, 4.1 percent increase from month before; lending rates fell to lowest rate since 1994, at 58.1 percent; government says April unemployment fell to 7.8 percent, down from 8.1 percent in March (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Brazilian bank lending rose in April for the 10th consecutive month as the economic recovery increased consumers' appetite for credit, the central bank said. Banks lent $33 billion in April, a 4.1 percent increase from the month before. Lending rates, while extremely high by United States standards, fell to the lowest rate since 1994, at 58.1 percent. In another sign of recovery in Latin America's largest economy, the government said April unemployment fell to 7.8 percent, down from 8.1 percent in March.</p>
        <p>Jennifer L. Rich</p>
      </block>
